text: I'm John Harwood with the New York Times
and CNBC the story line of Barack
Obama's campaign against Hillary Clinton
for the Democratic nomination has become
so familiar that we sometimes forget
what makes this race historically unique
but in its duration in its
competitiveness in its cost and level of
participation the 2008 Democratic
primary stands alone in American
presidential politics first of all the
duration this race started earlier than
ever on January 3rd in Iowa this primary
primary calendar last fully two months
longer than it did in 1968 40 years ago
second the level of competitiveness
usually once a primary candidate starts
losing they fade and drop out of the
race but after damaging defeats in
February Hillary Clinton has grown
stronger
she still commands 45% of the Democratic
convention delegates even as Barack
Obama has been widely seen as the likely
Democratic nominee third is the cost
barack obama and hillary clinton between
them have raised nearly 500 million
dollars shattering previous records
neither interestingly is a white male
and in the past the objection to black
or female candidates has been that they
couldn't raise the money they've proven
that that's not the case certainly with
these two candidates and finally the
level of participation Hillary Clinton
likes to say that she's gotten more
votes than any previous primary
candidate in American history that is
true more than 17 million votes but so
has Barack Obama and that's something to
concern the Republicans it appears that
Hillary Clinton's argument that she has
won the popular vote by including
Michigan and her tally isn't going to
carry the day with super-delegates
but here is what those super-delegates
may want to focus on and Republicans may
worry about in those races in Ohio West
Virginia Pennsylvania where Hillary
Clinton defeated Barack Obama by wide
margins Barack Obama got more votes in
defeat in the Democratic primary than
John McCain received in winning the
Republican primaries
